subject: A34YGHVPXQZVBX
comments: I wanted to preserve points, as either player X or Y.  As X, I knew that Y could retaliate much more strongly than I could hurt them, so I always chose B trusting they would choose D.  As player Y, I wanted to go with D too, I had no points to earn with option C, just harm to inflict on the other player.  I only employed C when the first player wouldn't play fair with me for several rounds of me trying to offer a Deal.  I was prepared to retaliate again if I needed to, but the first first player stayed a Collaborator.  Yes, I recognize the Prisoners' Dilemma, with some twists.

subject: A9ZS3JB9F24V4
comments: This was a very interesting game to play. My strategy was to go for option b if I was first, so 0 points would be taken from me and 0 points would be taken from my partner. When I did that, I hoped that my partner would see it as a sign of good faith, and choose the corresponding option that wouldn't take points away from either of us, so neither of us would lose our points at the end. However, when I was faced with one opponent who kept choosing option A and taking a point away from me, I retaliated by choosing option c (-1 point for me but -4 points for my partner) to make sure that I wouldn't lose all of my points.

comments: My strategy was if I'm as Role X, I don't initialize any behavior that will harm others(i.e. I don't choose Option A) unless Role Y started to harm me(i.e., Role Y chose Option C). If I'm in Role Y, if Role X started to harm me (i.e., choose Option A), I'll give him one more chance to correct his error(i.e., I'll choose Option D as a return), but if he continues choosing Option A, then I'll choose Option C to fight back until he switch to choosing Option B, then I'll switch to Option D accordingly.
